jakarta-ee-version-01000.description: Jakarta EE version not latest stable

incidents.message:
Your application is not using the latest Jakarta EE version. 
Upgrading to the latest stable version ensures better performance, security, and compatibility with modern tools.
  1. Pick a Supported Version: Review the Jakarta EE release versions and choose an actively supported version.
  2. Update Your Project: Change the Jakarta EE version in your pom.xml or build.gradle.
  3. Fix Compatibility Issues: Update deprecated code, replace removed features, and ensure dependencies are compatible with the new Jakarta EE version.
  4. Thoroughly Test: Run unit, integration, and end-to-end tests to make sure everything still works after the upgrade.

The application uses Spring Cloud Config for centralized configuration management. Consider migrating to Azure App Configuration.
Azure App Configuration provides a managed, centralized store for application settings and feature flags, with Spring integration for Spring Boot applications.
You will need to replace the Spring Cloud Config Server backend (and its repository/credentials) with Azure App Configuration, update client configuration to use the App Configuration integration, and migrate configuration keys and access control to Azure.

links.title: Use Azure App Configuration with Spring Boot
Azure App Configuration with Spring Boot (Spring Cloud Azure)
Use Azure App Configuration in Azure Kubernetes Service

incidents.message:
The application embeds the Eureka client. If you are migrating to Azure Container Apps, the connection info of Eureka can be injected upon app start.

 Find any explicit configurations of config server connection info:

 If configured in **configuration files**: they will be ignored and overrided by Azure Container Apps.

 If configured in **command line parameters**, **Java system attribute**, **environment variable**: they need to be removed or you might experience conflicts and unexpected behavior.

links.title: Connect to a managed Eureka Server for Spring in Azure Container Apps
Create a highly available Eureka server component cluster in Azure Container Apps
Integrate Admin for Spring with Eureka Server for Spring in Azure Container Apps

hardcoded-urls-00001.description: Avoid using hardcoded URLs (HTTP protocol) in source code

incidents.message: This patterns verifies in source code and configuration files the presence of hardcoded URLs using the HTTP protocol (HTTP/HTTPS). This URL would need to be replaced by the new resource's URL during the Cloud migration, if any change occured.

unsecure-network-protocol-00000.description: Use of unsecured network protocols or URI libraries

incidents.message:
Using secured protocols such as HTTPS and SFTP (over HTTP and FTP) should now be the norm as applications are more and more exposed and interconnected. 
This CloudReady patterns looks for unescured URI in the source code or deprecated URI libraries. 
Ideally, URLs should be replaced in your source code by secured protocols HTTPS and SFTP (and ensure the infrastructure implements these protocols for the resources your application calls, uses or references).
